==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pill
<hw>Pill</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be peeled; to peel off in
flakes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pill
<hw>Pill</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>pilare</ets> to
deprive of hair, and E. <ets>pill</ets>, n. (above).]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To deprive of hair; to make bald.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To peel; to make by removing the skin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Jacob] <qex>pilled</qex> white streaks . . . in the rods.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xxx. 37.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Pill
<hw>Pill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Pilled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Pilling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>piller</ets>,
L. <ets>pilare</ets>; cf. It. <ets>pigliare</ets> to take. Cf.
<er>Peel</er> to plunder.]</ety> <def>To rob; to plunder; to pillage; to
peel. See <er>Peel</er>, to plunder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pillers and robbers were come in to the field to <qex>pill</qex>
and to rob.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Malroy.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Pill
<hw>Pill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>pilute</ets>, L.
<ets>pilula</ets> a pill, little ball, dim. of L. <ets>pila</ets> a
ball. Cf. <er>Piles</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A medicine in the form
of a little ball, or small round mass, to be swallowed whole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Figuratively, something offensive or nauseous which
must be accepted or endured.</def><-- esp., as bitter pill -->
<rj><au>Udall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pill beetle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any small
beetle of the genus <gen>Byrrhus</gen>, having a rounded body, with the
head concealed beneath the thorax.</cd> -- <col><b>Pill bug</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any terrestrial isopod of the genus
<gen>Armadillo</gen>, having the habit of rolling itself into a ball
when disturbed. Called also <altname>pill wood
louse</altname>.</cd></cs><-- poison pill Fig., anything accompanying a
desirable object or action, which makes it deleterious to him who
accepts it; esp. (Finance) a provision in the regulations or financial
structure (as indebtedness) of a company which makes the company
undesirable as a target for a hostile takeover -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pillage</ent>⟦br⟧
